english:
  title: Preface to the Eight Masters Poetry Selection
  author: Choe Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the leisure hours of the Bihae Hall, I gathered with three other scholars of letters. From the collected works of eight great masters—Li Bai, Du Fu, Wei Yingwu, Liu Zongyuan, Ouyang Xiu, Wang Anshi, Su Shi, and Huang Tingjian—we selected regulated verses in both five and seven characters, arranging them into several volumes and naming this collection the Eight Masters Poetry Selection.

    Bright as shells strung together, layered like pearls on a cord, each poet's distinctive voice emerges while all conform to the measures of poetry. Reading these verses, one feels as if seated at a single table with all eight masters, their resonant harmonies ringing in one's ears—truly like discovering celestial music among a thousand flowers and discerning the sacred tone amid all other sounds.

    Alas, the Great Elegance has long departed, and the many voices that remain buzz like cicadas in summer. How drastically have the spirit, character, and forms of poetry been transformed! When we reach the Tang and Song dynasties, poetic forms were thoroughly perfected, and these eight masters alone held the keys to the gates. Their verses embody the remaining essence of the Three Classics and Three Modes, becoming beacons for all who truly study poetry.

    Yet the ancients debated whether regulated verse surpasses ancient verse in difficulty. Indeed, when poetry reaches the regulated form, the work becomes exquisite and demanding—even those called masters struggle to achieve perfection. The selectors of old were numerous, yet most merely relied on others' judgments to rank what they chose. Though some offered their own views, those who favored the plain and simple often descended into shallow vulgarity, while those who admired the strange and archaic frequently stumbled into dangerous eccentricity, inviting the ridicule of posterity.

    How much harder is the art of selection than the art of composition! Without reaching the profound depths of this craft, how can one truly discern what to reject and what to embrace? Yet the master of Bihae Hall possesses both refined scholarship and sweeping knowledge, extraordinary discernment that transcends the ordinary. Every word that flows from his brush naturally conforms to the proper forms. He flows with the creative forces of nature, his lofty spirit outsoaring the clouds; his rough jade and molten gold possess both commanding depth and elegant simplicity; his warm brightness and serene stability escape the worn paths of convention; his lotus swaying in the breeze competes with sun and moon in radiance. All these qualities shine forth in the everyday work of this master—one who truly gathers the great achievements of all schools and possesses the diamond-bright eye of perfect discernment.

    Therefore, this collection not only gathers the finest essences and selects the finest models, but avoids the stale categories of later critics while aligning with the subtle intentions of the ancient sages when they refined the three hundred poems. How could this be merely material for playful verse about wind and moonlight? Rather, it aims to establish itself as ancient wisdom, awakening those who come after, planting a standard in poetry's hall and establishing measures in the garden of words—to cleanse ten thousand ages of vulgar habit and continue the noble song of a thousand years. Such is the diligent intention behind this work.

    I myself am but one who presses his face against a wall in darkness when it comes to poetry. Yet beholding this selection, I can glimpse the very courtyards of the eight masters. What, then, might be granted to those more capable than I? I am confident that those who equal and surpass these eight masters, transcending both past and present, will steadily arise. The music of Great Elegance shall not want for creators. Is the benefit this selection brings to the Way of Poetry truly a small thing?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Eight Masters' refers to Li Bai (701-762), Du Fu (712-770), Wei Yingwu (737-792), Liu Zongyuan (773-819), Ouyang Xiu (1007-1072), Wang Anshi (1021-1086), Su Shi (1037-1101), and Huang Tingjian (1045-1105)—major poets spanning Tang and Song dynasties.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The ''Three Classics and Three Modes'' alludes to the structure of the Book of Poetry: the three sections (Wind, Elegance, Hymns) and three rhetorical modes (exposition, comparison, allusion).'
  - key: ''
    value: '''Regulated verse'' (律詩) refers to strict poetic forms with fixed tonal patterns and rhyme schemes that developed during the Tang dynasty.'
